1348–Overleden","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1300–1320":"1300–1320","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1290":"1290","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1348":"circa 1348","after 1341":"na 1341","about 1320":"circa 1320","1328":"1328","Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England":"Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England","Disserth, Radnorshire, Wales":"Disserth, Radnorshire, Wales","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lechlade, Gloucestershire, England":"Lechlade-On-Thames, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1320–1378":"1320–1378","1315–1341":"1315–1341","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1341–1415":"1341–1415","1348–Female":"1348–Deceased","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1300–1320":"1300–1320","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1290":"1290","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1348":"about 1348","after 1341":"after 1341","about 1320":"about 1320","1328":"1328","Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England":"Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England","Disserth, Radnorshire, Wales":"Disserth, Radnorshire, Wales","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Lechlade, Gloucestershire, England":"Lechlade-On-Thames, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rosser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>R(h)osier</i>, equivalent to English   Roger  . See   Prosser  .","German (also <b>Rösser</b>): occupational name for a horse farmer, dealer, a groom, or a carter, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>ros</i> ‘horse, steed’.","German (<b>Rösser</b>): topographic name from Middle High German <i>rœsse</i> ‘pool for retting flax’. Compare   Roesser  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Roger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Roesser","meanings":["German (<b>Rösser</b>): see   Rosser  ."]},{"name":"Russaw","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Rosser  ."]}]},{"name":"'Gwalter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Walthers","meanings":["German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Walther</i> (see   Walter  )."]},{"name":"McQuate","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uait</b> ‘son of <i>Uat</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Irish form   McQuaid  ."]},{"name":"Waltke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Jurgen, Wilhelmina.","German: from a pet form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names formed with Old High German <i>waltan</i> ‘to rule’ as the first element, as in   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McWaters","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of the personal name   Walter  , with excrescent English <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wahler","meanings":["German:","from the personal name <i>Wol(d)er</i>, Low German form of   Walter  .","habitational name for someone from any of various places called Wahl, Wahle, or Wahlen."]},{"name":"McWalter","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b> ‘son of   Walter  ’."]},{"name":"Walters","meanings":["English: variant of   Walter  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Walther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Wolfgang, Otto, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Bernd, Bernhard.","German, Dutch, Swedish, and Danish: variant of   Walter  ."]},{"name":"Lauter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Erwin, Kurt, Sigismund, Wolf.","German: topographic name and habitational name, from a common stream name meaning ‘clear’, from Middle High German <i>hlutra</i>, or from any of the places called Lauter or Lauta (Saxony). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and some other European countries.","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Lavtar</b> or its Croatized and rare Slovenian variant <b>Lautar</b>: from a dialect variant of the personal name <i>Valter</i> (see   Walter  )."]}]},{"name":"Sais'","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fernando, Orlando, Angelita, Arturo, Delfina, Desiderio, Dionicio, Edgardo, Elva, Fidel, Isidoro, Jere.","Catalan: topographic name from <i>saix</i> ‘rock’ (from Latin <i>saxum</i>), or an ethnic name for a Saxon, derived from the root of <i>saxó</i> ‘Saxon’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"Vaughan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the Welsh surname, in origin a nickname from the mutated form (<i>fychan</i> in Welsh orthography) of the Welsh adjective <i>bychan</i> ‘small’."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughn","meanings":["Transferred use of the Welsh surname, in origin a nickname from the mutated form (<i>fychan</i> in Welsh orthography) of the Welsh adjective <i>bychan</i> ‘small’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","juris